images.alt: In 2217, Orin Shaw, an unhoused man with an old non-surveillant CoreTag, becomes the compatible host for the Afterglow, a centuries-accumulated lattice of discarded simulations that quietly rides public sleep-pod nanoseeds. Each night adds “rings” to his body, making him faster, stronger, and perceptually sharper, while an ethical lock prevents lethal escalation and a built-in overlay lets him purge or halt the process at any time. Forced into a visible survival state, he first saves a child during a scaffold failure, then exposes “Gratitude Harvesters” staging disasters to farm social credit, disabling their jammer and redirecting a collapsing loader with nonlethal precision. Rejecting recruitment and celebrity, he files as SOURCE OPT-OUT: Defensive Only and chooses Partial Retention, freezing his enhancements at a deliberate level. He keeps using pods for rest but no longer grows, intervening rarely and precisely while the city’s humane, non-coercive systems leave him alone. Somewhere in forgotten caches, the Afterglow persists, patient, available to complete itself again if another corridor opens.
